Q1. Introduction to Compliance within FinTech (15 Marks)
Introduction

Compliance in FinTech means following laws, regulations, security standards, and industry rules while providing digital financial services such as payments, wallets, banking apps, cards, and online transactions.

It ensures that organizations operate legally, securely, and ethically.

Compliance is important because FinTech companies deal with:

Customer money
Personal data
Payment systems
Sensitive financial records

Without compliance, organizations may face fraud, cyber attacks, penalties, and loss of trust.

Objectives of Compliance in FinTech
Protect customer data
Prevent fraud and cybercrime
Follow legal requirements
Maintain trust in digital finance
Ensure safe transactions
Reduce business risk
Common Compliance Areas in FinTech
Data privacy
Cyber security
Anti-money laundering (AML)
Know Your Customer (KYC)
Payment security
Consumer protection
Regulatory reporting
Importance of Compliance
1. Legal Protection

Helps avoid fines and penalties.

2. Customer Trust

Users feel safe using services.

3. Security

Protects systems from threats.

4. Smooth Business Operations

Creates standard processes.

5. Market Growth

Encourages innovation responsibly.

Conclusion

Compliance is the foundation of safe and trusted FinTech systems. It helps companies grow while protecting customers and following the law.

Q1 (a) Describe Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS)
Introduction

PCI DSS stands for Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard.

It is a global security standard designed to protect credit card and debit card data during transactions.

It is managed by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council (PCI SSC).

Purpose of PCI DSS
Protect cardholder data
Prevent payment fraud
Secure card transactions
Build trust in online payments
Who Must Follow PCI DSS?

Any organization that:

Accepts card payments
Processes transactions
Stores card data

Examples:

Banks
Payment gateways
Online shopping websites
FinTech companies
Retail stores
Main Requirements of PCI DSS
1. Build Secure Network

Use firewalls and secure systems.

2. Protect Card Data

Encrypt stored and transmitted data.

3. Manage Vulnerabilities

Use antivirus and updates.

4. Strong Access Control

Only authorized users can access data.

5. Monitor Networks

Track logs and perform testing.

6. Security Policy

Train employees and define rules.

Benefits
Reduces data breaches
Protects customer data
Avoids penalties
Improves reputation
Conclusion

PCI DSS is essential for secure card payments and protecting sensitive financial information.

Q1 (b) Describe RBI PSS (Reserve Bank of India – Payment and Settlement Systems)
Introduction

RBI PSS refers to the Payment and Settlement Systems Act, 2007 regulated by the Reserve Bank of India.

It provides the legal framework for digital payment systems in India.

Objectives
Regulate payment systems
Ensure secure transactions
Protect customers
Promote digital payments
Maintain financial stability
Systems Covered
UPI
NEFT
RTGS
IMPS
Wallets
Card systems
Payment gateways
Role of RBI Under PSS
1. Authorization

Approves payment system operators.

2. Regulation

Issues rules and standards.

3. Monitoring

Checks security and compliance.

4. Consumer Protection

Handles complaints and fraud guidelines.

5. Settlement Management

Ensures smooth fund transfer between banks.

Importance
Builds trust in digital payments
Prevents fraud
Supports innovation
Creates secure ecosystem
Conclusion

RBI PSS is the backbone of India’s digital payment regulation system.

Q2. Introduction to Software Composition Analysis (SCA) – Security Case Study (15 Marks)
Introduction

Software Composition Analysis (SCA) is a security process used to identify, analyze, and manage open-source and third-party software components used in an application.

Modern applications depend on many libraries. If these components contain vulnerabilities, attackers can exploit them.

Security Case Study
Background

A FinTech company develops a wallet app using:

Open-source login library
Encryption package
Payment APIs

The development team uses old components without security checks.

Problem

One library contains a known vulnerability.

An attacker exploits it and:

Steals customer data
Accesses transaction details
Causes fraud
Impact
Financial loss
Data breach
Reputation damage
Compliance failure
Applying SCA

The company uses an SCA tool.

Steps
Scan components
Identify versions
Check vulnerabilities
Suggest updates
Block risky release
Benefits
Early risk detection
Secure software supply chain
Better compliance
Supports DevSecOps
Tools
Snyk
OWASP Dependency-Check
Black Duck
Mend
Conclusion

SCA is important because it secures applications by detecting risky third-party components before deployment.
